packageMeta.name: purescript-httpure
packageMeta.description: A web framework written in PureScript.

header, if there is any.

declarations.comments:
The `Headers` type is just sugar for a `Object` of `Strings`
that represents the set of headers in an HTTP request or response.
declarations.title: Headers

declarations.comments: Convert an `Array` of `Tuples` of 2 `Strings` to a `Headers` object.
declarations.title: headers

declarations.comments: Create a singleton header from a key-value pair.
declarations.title: header

declarations.comments:
Given some type and a key on that type, extract some value that
corresponds to that key.
declarations.title: lookup

declarations.comments:
This simple helper works on any `Lookup` instance, where the container set
has a single type variable, and returns a `Boolean` indicating if the given
key matches any value in the given container.
declarations.title: has

declarations.comments:
This simple helper works on any `Lookup` instance where the return type is
a `Monoid`, and is the same as `lookup` except that it returns a `t`
instead of a `Maybe t`. If `lookup` would return `Nothing`, then `at`
returns `mempty`.
declarations.title: at

declarations.comments:
`!!` is inspired by `!!` in `Data.Array`, but note that it differs from
`!!` in `Data.Array` in that you can use `!!` for any other instance of
`Lookup`.
These are the HTTP methods that HTTPure understands.
declarations.title: Method

declarations.comments:
The `Path` type is just sugar for an `Array` of `String` segments that are
sent in a request and indicates the path of the resource being requested.
Note that this type has an implementation of `Lookup` for `Int` keys
defined by `lookupArray` in [Lookup.purs](./Lookup.purs) because
`lookupArray` is defined for any `Array` of `Monoids`. So you can do
something like `path !! 2` to get the path segment at index 2.
declarations.title: Path

declarations.comments:
The `Request` type is a `Record` type that includes fields for accessing
the different parts of the HTTP request.
declarations.title: Request

declarations.comments:
Return the full resolved path, including query parameters. This may not
match the requested path--for instance, if there are empty path segments in
the request--but it is equivalent.
declarations.title: fullPath

declarations.comments:
The `ResponseM` type simply conveniently wraps up an HTTPure monad that
returns a response. This type is the return type of all router/route
methods.
declarations.title: ResponseM

declarations.comments: The same as `response` but with headers.
declarations.title: response'

declarations.comments:
For custom response statuses or providing a body for response codes that
don't typically send one.
declarations.title: response

declarations.comments: The same as `emptyResponse` but with headers.
declarations.title: emptyResponse'

declarations.comments: The same as `response` but without a body.
declarations.title: emptyResponse

declarations.comments:
The `ServerM` type simply conveniently wraps up an HTTPure monad that
returns a `Unit`. This type is the return type of the HTTPure serve and
related methods.
declarations.title: ServerM

declarations.comments:
Given a `Options HTTPS.SSLOptions` object and a `HTTP.ListenOptions`
object, a function mapping `Request` to `ResponseM`, and a `ServerM`
containing effects to run on boot, creates and runs a HTTPure server with
SSL.
declarations.title: serveSecure'

declarations.comments:
Create and start an SSL server. This method is the same as `serve`, but
takes additional SSL arguments.  The arguments in order are:
1. A port number
2. A path to a cert file
3. A path to a private key file
4. A handler method which maps `Request` to `ResponseM`
5. A callback to call when the server is up
declarations.title: serveSecure

declarations.comments:
Given a `ListenOptions` object, a function mapping `Request` to
`ResponseM`, and a `ServerM` containing effects to run on boot, creates and
runs a HTTPure server without SSL.
declarations.title: serve'

declarations.comments:
Create and start a server. This is the main entry point for HTTPure. Takes
a port number on which to listen, a function mapping `Request` to
`ResponseM`, and a `ServerM` containing effects to run after the server has
booted (usually logging). Returns an `ServerM` containing the server's
effects.
declarations.title: serve

declarations.comments:
The `Body` type is just sugar for a `String`, that will be sent or received
in the HTTP body.
declarations.title: Body

declarations.comments: Extract the contents of the body of the HTTP `Request`.
declarations.title: read

declarations.comments: Write a `Body` to the given HTTP `Response` and close it.
declarations.title: write

children.comments:
Given some type and a key on that type, extract some value that
corresponds to that key.
children.title: lookup

children.comments:
The instance of `Lookup` for an `Array` is just `!!` as defined in
`Data.Array`.
children.title: lookupArray

children.comments:
The instance of `Lookup` for a `Object` just uses `Object.lookup` (but
flipped, because `Object.lookup` expects the key first, which would end up
with a really weird API for `!!`).
children.title: lookupObject

declarations.comments:
Types that implement the `Lookup` class can be looked up by some key to
retrieve some value. For instance, you could have an implementation for
`String Int String` where `lookup s i` returns `Just` a `String` containing
the character in `s` at `i`, or `Nothing` if `i` is out of bounds.
declarations.title: Lookup

declarations.comments:
This simple helper works on any `Lookup` instance where the return type is
a `Monoid`, and is the same as `lookup` except that it returns a `t`
instead of a `Maybe t`. If `lookup` would return `Nothing`, then `at`
returns `mempty`.
declarations.title: at

declarations.comments:
This simple helper works on any `Lookup` instance, where the container set
has a single type variable, and returns a `Boolean` indicating if the given
key matches any value in the given container.
declarations.title: has

declarations.comments:
`!!` is inspired by `!!` in `Data.Array`, but note that it differs from
`!!` in `Data.Array` in that you can use `!!` for any other instance of
`Lookup`.
These are the HTTP methods that HTTPure understands.
declarations.title: Method

declarations.comments: Take an HTTP `Request` and extract the `Method` for that request.
declarations.title: read

declarations.comments:
The `Path` type is just sugar for an `Array` of `String` segments that are
sent in a request and indicates the path of the resource being requested.
Note that this type has an implementation of `Lookup` for `Int` keys
defined by `lookupArray` in [Lookup.purs](./Lookup.purs) because
`lookupArray` is defined for any `Array` of `Monoids`. So you can do
something like `path !! 2` to get the path segment at index 2.
declarations.title: Path

declarations.comments: Given an HTTP `Request` object, extract the `Path`.
declarations.title: read

declarations.comments:
The `Query` type is a `Object` of `Strings`, with one entry per query
parameter in the request. For any query parameters that don't have values
(`/some/path?query`), the value in the `Object` for that parameter will be
the string `"true"`. Note that this type has an implementation of `Lookup`
for `String` keys defined by `lookupObject` in [Lookup.purs](./Lookup.purs)
because `lookupObject` is defined for any `Object` of `Monoids`. So you can
do something like `query !! "foo"` to get the value of the query parameter
"foo".
declarations.title: Query

declarations.comments: The `Map` of query segments in the given HTTP `Request`.
declarations.title: read

declarations.comments:
The `Request` type is a `Record` type that includes fields for accessing
the different parts of the HTTP request.
declarations.title: Request

declarations.comments:
Given an HTTP `Request` object, this method will convert it to an HTTPure
`Request` object.
declarations.title: fromHTTPRequest

declarations.comments:
Return the full resolved path, including query parameters. This may not
match the requested path--for instance, if there are empty path segments in
the request--but it is equivalent.
declarations.title: fullPath

declarations.comments: A `Response` is a status code, headers, and a body.
declarations.title: Response

declarations.comments:
The `ResponseM` type simply conveniently wraps up an HTTPure monad that
returns a response. This type is the return type of all router/route
methods.
declarations.title: ResponseM

declarations.comments:
Given an HTTP `Response` and a HTTPure `Response`, this method will return
a monad encapsulating writing the HTTPure `Response` to the HTTP `Response`
and closing the HTTP `Response`.
declarations.title: send

declarations.comments:
For custom response statuses or providing a body for response codes that
don't typically send one.
declarations.title: response

declarations.comments: The same as `response` but with headers.
declarations.title: response'

declarations.comments: The same as `response` but without a body.
declarations.title: emptyResponse

declarations.comments: The same as `emptyResponse` but with headers.
declarations.title: emptyResponse'
